,"meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gregg  ."]},{"name":"Greggs","meanings":["English: variant of   Gregg  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Gregson","meanings":["English (Lancashire): patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Greg</i> (see   Gregg  ), a short form of the personal name   Gregory   + <i>son</i>."]},{"name":"Gregory","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: from a personal name that was popular throughout Christendom in the Middle Ages. The Greek original, <i>Grēgorios</i>, is a derivative of <i>grēgorein</i> ‘to be awake, to be watchful’. However, the Latin form, <i>Gregorius</i>, came to be associated by folk etymology with <i>grex</i>, <i>gregis</i> ‘flock, herd’, under the influence of the Christian image of the good shepherd. The Greek name was borne in the early Christian centuries by two fathers of the Orthodox Church, Saint Gregory Nazianzene (<i>c.</i> 325–390) and Saint Gregory of Nyssa (<i>c.</i> 331–395), and later by sixteen popes, starting with Gregory the Great (<i>c.</i> 540–604). It was also the name of 3rd- and 4th-century apostles of Armenia. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Gregorio  , German, Slovak, and Slovenian   Gregor  , Polish <b>Grzegorz</b>, Czech <b>Řehoř</b> (see   Rehor  ), and French   Gregoire  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Polish   Grzegorczyk  ."]},{"name":"Gragg","meanings":["English: variant of   Gregg   and possibly also of   Cragg  ."]},{"name":"Greg","meanings":["English: variant of   Gregg  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alexander Gregg was born on 1 January 1680, in Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland as the son of William Gregg and Jean Brown. He had at least 1 daughter with Isabell Lead."},"et":{"1 January 1680–":"1. jaanuar 1680–Surnud","1677–Male":"1677–Surnud","1680–Male":"1680–Surnud","1680–Female":"1680–Surnud","1697–1770":"1697–1770","1659–Male":"1659–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","4 August 1670":"4. august 1670","6 November 1697":"6. november 1697","1677":"1677","1697":"1697","1770":"1770","1 January 1680":"1. jaanuar 1680","1680":"1680","01 JAN 1680":"1. jaanuar 1680","1659":"1659","Monquhitter, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Monquhitter, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","St Nicholas, Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"St Nicholas, Aberdeen, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1 January 1680–":"1. tammikuuta 1680–Kuollut","1677–Male":"1677–Kuollut","1680–Male":"1680–Kuollut","1680–Female":"1680–Kuollut","1697–1770":"1697–1770","1659–Male":"1659–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","4 August 1670":"4. elokuuta 1670","6 November 1697":"6. marraskuuta 1697","1677":"1677","1697":"1697","1770":"1770","1 January 1680":"1. tammikuuta 1680","1680":"1680","01 JAN 1680":"1. tammikuuta 1680","1659":"1659","Monquhitter, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Monquhitter, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","St Nicholas, Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"St Nicholas, Aberdeen, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1 January 1680–":"1 janvier 1680–Décédé","1677–Male":"1677–Décédé","1680